---
title: Scroll Snap Carousel
description: A horizontal carousel using `scroll-snap-type` and `scroll-snap-align`.
slug: scroll-carousel
cssFile: scroll-carousel.css
explanation: <code>scroll-snap-type:x mandatory</code> on the container forces snapping after each scroll gesture. <code>scroll-snap-align:start</code> on each slide defines where it snaps to. The container is just a flex row with <code>overflow-x:auto</code>. No JS, no next/prev buttons required — the browser handles the snapping physics.
---
{% extends "example.njk" %}
{% block demo %}
<div class="carousel-wrap">
	<div class="carousel">
		<div class="carousel-slide">Slide 1 of 5</div>
		<div class="carousel-slide">Slide 2 of 5</div>
		<div class="carousel-slide">Slide 3 of 5</div>
		<div class="carousel-slide">Slide 4 of 5</div>
		<div class="carousel-slide">Slide 5 of 5</div>
	</div>
	<p class="carousel-hint">← scroll or swipe →</p>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block html_code %}
{%- highlight "html" %}
<div class="carousel">
  <div class="carousel-slide">Slide 1</div>
  <div class="carousel-slide">Slide 2</div>
  <div class="carousel-slide">Slide 3</div>
</div>
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block css_code %}
{%- highlight "css" %}
.carousel {
  display: flex;
  overflow-x: auto;
  scroll-snap-type: x mandatory;
  gap: 1rem;
}

.carousel-slide {
  flex: 0 0 200px;
  height: 130px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  scroll-snap-align: start;
}
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block notes %}
<section class="explanation-section">
	<h2>JavaScript needed for drag</h2>
	<p>Click-and-drag scrolling on desktop is a browser limitation — <code>overflow-x: auto</code> containers don't respond to mouse drag without JavaScript pointer event handlers. Scrollwheel on desktop and touch swipe on mobile work natively with pure CSS.</p>
</section>
{% endblock %}
